doc.after: The Economy of Liverpool is one of the largest within the United Kingdom, sitting at the centre of one of the two core economies within the North West of England.[123] In 2006, the city's GVA was Â£7,626 million, providing a per capita figure of Â£17,489, which was above the North West average.[124] After several decades of decline, Liverpool's economy has seen somewhat of a revival since the mid-1990s, with its GVA increasing 71.8% between 1995 and 2006 and employment increasing 12% between 1998 and 2006.[124]
